	#network = regression(network, optimizer= Optimizer(name='adam',learning_rate=0.00005),loss='categorical_crossentropy',learning_rate=0.001);
	model = tflearn.DNN(network,tensorboard_verbose=1,checkpoint_path=network_directory+"convolutional_nerve_identifier.ckpt",tensorboard_dir=models_path+'tensorboard');	#
	model.fit(images_array,masks_array,n_epoch=epoch,batch_size=batch,show_metric=True);
	
	model.save(network_directory+"CNN_YES_NO_CLASSIFIER.tfl");
	tensorflow.reset_default_graph() ;

## Issue description
Hi, I've been using pybind11 successfully for a number of projects lately, but I'm having an issue with my current project and would appreciate some feedback from the more experienced users or devs.

Basically, I have a 3rd party C++ library, the issue with it's API can be summed down to this (full example file in a gist linked below):
```c++
struct B;
struct A {
	A() {};
	~A() {
		printf("~A()\n");
		if (!b_list.empty()) {
			printf("b_list not empty!\n");
		}
	};
	void register_b(B *b) {
		b_list.push_back(b);
	};
	void unregister_b(B *b) {
		auto removed = std::remove(b_list.begin(), b_list.end(), b);
		b_list.erase(removed, b_list.end());
	};
	std::list<B *> b_list;
};

struct B {
	B(A& a) : m_a(a) {
		m_a.register_b(this);
	};
	~B() {
		printf("~B()\n");
		m_a.unregister_b(this);
	};
	A& m_a;
};
```

Which means the user is supposed to make sure that A is destructed after all B's created with that A are destructed. I know the API can be much better, but being 3rd party I don't have much choice in the matter.

I tried using pybind11 to create a module for this interface:
```c++
PYBIND11_MODULE(example, m) {
	py::class_<B>(m, "B");
	py::class_<A>(m, "A")
		.def(py::init<>())
		.def("get_b_list", [](A& _this) ->  std::list<B> {
			std::list<B> b_list
			// Note: Actual enumeration code omitted, 
			// 	I just create some items to demonstrate the issue.
			b_list.push_back({_this});
			b_list.push_back({_this});
			return b_list;
		}, py::return_value_policy::move);
}
```

And use it with a simple test script:
```python
import example
a = example.A()
b1 = a.get_b_list()
print b1
```

This attempt does not work because I don't convey the dependancies to python, and so A may be destructed before all of the B's and I get the print message in A's destructor (which is an assert in the actual library).

After going through the docs, I saw the `keep_alive` option and thought I should add it to `get_b_list` defs: `py::return_value_policy::move, py::keep_alive<0, 1>());` (we want A to be destroyed only after the list, and therefore after its items, are destructed)

This leads to the following error: `RuntimeError: Could not allocate weak reference!`. Which makes sense because python doesn't support weakrefs to lists :(

This leaves me with three options:
1. There's a better way to do this which is already integrated into pybind11 but I haven't figured it out yet.
2. lists+weakrefs makes sense as a feature request for pybind11. I went down that rabbit hole for a couple of hours and got somewhere, but it's *really* hacky.
3. Wrap the API in a way that preserves the destruction condition in C++.

I ended going with 3, I don't want to clutter this post with more code so please find it here: https://gist.github.com/blapid/69cba9f58abf38ecb84a0d3c1a241fef .

I post this issue with two goals:
1. If I missed anything, and option 1 is correct, I'd love to hear about the correct approach.
2. If anyone else is having this issue, I hope my API wrapping idea may be useful for them as well.

Cheers!
